post_cb({"25797439": {"ParentId": "25797291", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>According to the C++ Standard (7.1.2 Function specifiers)</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_25797291_25797439_0\">5 The virtual specifier shall be used <strong>only in the initial\n  declaration</strong> of a non-static class member function;</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "2877241", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "25797439", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2014-09-11T21:44:23.773", "LastActivityDate": "2014-09-11T21:44:23.773"}, "25797291": {"CommentCount": "4", "ViewCount": "4867", "CreationDate": "2014-09-11T21:33:06.227", "LastActivityDate": "2014-09-11T21:48:15.393", "Title": "Should a virtual c++ method implementation in .cpp file be marked virtual?", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "25797291", "Score": "6", "Body": "<p>I have a virtual C++ method that I'm defining in a .h file and implementing in a .cc file.  Should the implementation in the .cc file be marked virtual, or just the declaration in the .h file?  E.g., my header has:</p>\n<pre><code>virtual std::string toString() const;\n</code></pre>\n<p>The method is implemented in my .cc:</p>\n<pre><code>std::string\nMyObject::toString() const {\n   [implementation code]\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Should the implementation be marked virtual, or is the above code OK?  Does it matter?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><oop>", "OwnerUserId": "2199456", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "25797332": {"ParentId": "25797291", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>C++ Standard n3337 <strong>\u00a7</strong>  7.1.2/5 says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_25797291_25797332_0\">The virtual specifier shall be used only in the initial declaration of\n  a non-static class member function;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Keyword <code>virtual</code> can be used only inside class definition, when you declare (or define) the method. So... it can be used in implementation file but if it is still in class definition.</p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<pre><code>class A {\n    public:\n    virtual void f();\n};\n\nvirtual void A::f() {}  // error: \u2018virtual\u2019 outside class declaration\n                        // virtual void A::f() {}\n\nint main() {\n    // your code goes here\n    return 0;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p><a href=\"http://ideone.com/eiN7bd\">http://ideone.com/eiN7bd</a></p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "1141471", "LastEditorUserId": "1141471", "LastEditDate": "2014-09-11T21:48:15.393", "Id": "25797332", "Score": "10", "CreationDate": "2014-09-11T21:35:21.000", "LastActivityDate": "2014-09-11T21:48:15.393"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_25797291_25797332_0": {"section_id": 5405, "quality": 0.8888888888888888, "length": 8}, "so_25797291_25797439_0": {"section_id": 5405, "quality": 0.8888888888888888, "length": 8}}, "n3337": {"so_25797291_25797332_0": {"section_id": 5200, "quality": 0.8888888888888888, "length": 8}, "so_25797291_25797439_0": {"section_id": 5200, "quality": 0.8888888888888888, "length": 8}}, "n4659": {"so_25797291_25797332_0": {"section_id": 6827, "quality": 0.8888888888888888, "length": 8}, "so_25797291_25797439_0": {"section_id": 6827, "quality": 0.8888888888888888, "length": 8}}}});